<br>
I found out yesterday a friend of mine died from brain cancer. In February. Right now I'm pretty devastated, and I'm having difficulty separating the grief from the guilt. I'm saddened by his passing, but I'm feel really badly that those of us who worked with him for three or four years didn't find out until over three months after the fact.<br>
<br>
In our defense, several of the people I had to speak to today told me they had emailed him earlier this year, but his parents said they couldn't find contact information for any of us. We only found out when my RL fianceé sent out our save-the-date announcements and his mother emailed us.<br>
<br>
Does it make me a shitty friend that he's dead and I didn't know? I mean, fuck, I haven't talked to my own <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">father</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> in over two years.<br>
<br>
No condolences please, just answer the question. Should I have tried harder to keep in contact? Am I a bad person for being relatively diffident and stand-offish unless I think there's something important to say?<br>
<br>
(heh, hypocrisy is my friend: no pity, but please feed me validation  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :rolleyes --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/eyes.gif ALT=":rolleyes"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> ) <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=daliondveldrin>Dalion DVeldrin</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I put the inky in kinky</span><br>  Posts: 1070<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(5/23/03 5:29 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm57.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=245.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.animationlibrary.com/Animation11/Animals/Rabbits/Realistic_bunny_2.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Am I a bad friend?</span><hr size=1> In my opinion, no. You are not a bad friend. People make friends and eventually tend to drift apart and lose contact, thats pretty natural. At least you are grieving for him, if you were'nt then perhaps you are a bad friend. <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center"><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.screamparks.net/eqsigs/images/hosted/dalion.jpg"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></div><!--EZCODE CENTER END--><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center"><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=209679">Keeper of the Bunny Slippers: Flopsy and Mopsy</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--></div><!--EZCODE CENTER END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=melydia>Melydia</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 60<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(5/24/03 12:07 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm57.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=245.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Am I a bad friend?</span><hr size=1> I would have to agree with Dalion. It is hard to keep up a relationship if you don't see someone very often, no matter how close of friends you were. I am just graduating from college now, and I keep in contact with some of my friends from high school, but the time in between e-mails or whatever can be up to six months sometimes. I just tend not to say anything unless I have something relatively important to say. For some of them, it might be a long time before I found out if something happened to them, but that doesn't mean I wouldn't care. <br>
<br>
Anyway, I think that guilt is a natural reaction to death. Even for people who don't lose touch from each other might feel guilty. For instance, someone might feel bad because the last time they saw their friend alive, they had gotten mad at them over something stupid. <br>
<br>
In my opinion, the time it took for you to find out is less important than your reaction after finding out. (After all, its not like your friend, who had your contact information, could e-mail you and tell you the news. You can't help that his parents didn't have the information.) The important thing is that you still care about what happened to your friend.<br>
 <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center"><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://photopile.com/photos/melydia/ezboard/11310.jpg" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
